04196nam a22005415i 9780226090542DE-B159720200424112023.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200424t20142014ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802260905427 a10.7208/97802260905422doi  a(DE-B1597)525079  a(OCoLC)870228719  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQE13.C6bS54 2014eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a555.11 aShen, Grace Yen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnearthing the Nation :bModern Geology and Nationalism in Republican China /cGrace Yen Shen. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2014] 4cÂ©2014  a1 online resource (272 p.) :b3 halftones  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tINTRODUCTION. Science, Nation, and Chinese Modernity -- tONE. The Lay of the Land: Territoriality, Foreign Exploration, and Modern Geology in Qing China -- tTWO. Shaping the Field: Fieldwork and the Creation of the Modern Chinese Geologist -- tTHREE. A Host of Nations: Cosmopolitanism and the Geological Society of China -- tTHREE. A Host of Nations: Cosmopolitanism and the Geological Society of China -- tFIVE. Resistance and Reconstruction: Emergence of a Domestic Community -- tConclusion. Grounded Visions -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tSelected Bibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aQuestions of national identity have long dominated China's political, social, and cultural horizons. So in the early 1900s, when diverse groups in China began to covet foreign science in the name of new technology and modernization, questions of nationhood came to the fore. In Unearthing the Nation, Grace Yen Shen uses the development of modern geology to explore this complex relationship between science and nationalism in Republican China. Shen shows that Chinese geologists-in battling growing Western and Japanese encroachment of Chinese sovereignty-faced two ongoing challenges: how to develop objective, internationally recognized scientific authority without effacing native identity, and how to serve China when China was still searching for a stable national form. Shen argues that Chinese geologists overcame these obstacles by experimenting with different ways to associate the subjects of their scientific study, the land and its features, with the object of their political and cultural loyalties. This, in turn, led them to link national survival with the establishment of scientific authority in Chinese society. The first major history of modern Chinese geology, Unearthing the Nation introduces the key figures in the rise of the field, as well as several key organizations, such as the Geological Society of China, and explains how they helped bring Chinese geology onto the world stage.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aGeologistszChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aGeologyzChinaxHistoryy20th century. 0aNationalism and science. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUChP eBook-Package 2014-2016z978311070422840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226090542423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226090542.jpg  a978-3-11-069043-9  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  a978-3-11-070422-8  UChP eBook-Package 2014-2016c2014d2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles